<div id="review_1260059699" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1260059699" />
    <a title="Robert Samuels" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/42351068-robert-samuels"><img alt="Robert Samuels" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1260059699?book_show_action=true">Apr 20, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Robert Samuels" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Robert Samuels" href="/user/show/42351068-robert-samuels">Robert Samuels</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1260059699" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14169844805661734900">I was wholly captivated by this book. I&apos;ve been following the writer, James Grissom, for about three years through his blog, and I couldn&apos;t see how the book would live up to my expectations, but it did. I love the story of this kid writing to the great playwright Tennessee Williams and then being given an assignment, when what he wanted was advice--and, I think, assurance that a life in the theater was worthwhile. The insight from Williams is remarkable, but I love the chapters on Maureen Staple</span>
  <span id="freeText14169844805661734900" style="display:none">I was wholly captivated by this book. I've been following the writer, James Grissom, for about three years through his blog, and I couldn't see how the book would live up to my expectations, but it did. I love the story of this kid writing to the great playwright Tennessee Williams and then being given an assignment, when what he wanted was advice--and, I think, assurance that a life in the theater was worthwhile. The insight from Williams is remarkable, but I love the chapters on Maureen Stapleton, Jessica Tandy, Kim Stanley, Katharine Hepburn, Marian Seldes, and Jo Van Fleet. The conclusion of the book is devastating. I recently went to a reading of the book, and there in the audience were people who have been a part of this journey with Grissom for thirty years, and it was amazing to see it all come together. I highly recommend this book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14169844805661734900" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
