<div id="review_2551454355" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2551454355" />
    <a title="Gerri Corrado" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/25360397-gerri-corrado"><img alt="Gerri Corrado" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2551454355?book_show_action=true">Oct 18, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Gerri Corrado" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Gerri Corrado" href="/user/show/25360397-gerri-corrado">Gerri Corrado</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2551454355" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5142030026922368786">A friend of mine had tried reading a different bio of Tennessee Williams, and he told me he had to put it down because he said it just pounded away at self-indulgence and Tennessee&apos;s apparent joy at wallowing in his own misery. I was wary of reading Follies of God because I feared encountering the same phenomenon. What I found, however, was something quite different and unexpected. This bio is shaped by the writer&apos;s narrative of his experience with Williams and his meeting with most of Tennessee</span>
  <span id="freeText5142030026922368786" style="display:none">A friend of mine had tried reading a different bio of Tennessee Williams, and he told me he had to put it down because he said it just pounded away at self-indulgence and Tennessee's apparent joy at wallowing in his own misery. I was wary of reading Follies of God because I feared encountering the same phenomenon. What I found, however, was something quite different and unexpected. This bio is shaped by the writer's narrative of his experience with Williams and his meeting with most of Tennessee's "women of the fog" - an array of women of whom Tennessee was in awe, and most of whom appeared in his plays or movie adaptations of his plays. Williams spoke often of a fog that would rise and surround him when he was at his most creative, a fog out of which would appear his timeless characters, the great preponderance of them women. Later in his life, he befriended the author and asked him to go visit many of these accomplished actresses, some of whom had been close friends of his at times in his life, and ask them what they thought of Tennessee -- if he mattered to them. The author did this, but also brought to these women the reminiscenses Williams had stated about them. Most of these women were astounded that Williams revered them to the extent he did, and most of them offered their candid thoughts on the man and his genius. The book, written after the death of Williams, is an incredibly insightful account of the theater "back in the day," of a host of superb stage and screen legends, and most importantly, a view into facets of the monumental talents and trials of Tennessee Williams. I didn't want the book to end.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5142030026922368786" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

