        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2483294869" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18148795549227183590">This book gets five stars for what&apos;s best about it, the insights it gives into women (and some men) who were important collaborators with Tennessee Williams. In particular, Mr. Grissom provides rare biographical insights on such neglected actresses as Lois Smith, Barbara Baxley, Jo van Fleet, Kim Hunter and Kim Stanley. As a running subtheme, there&apos;s also a history of the Actor&apos;s Studio, with Maureen Stapleton, Geraldine Page and Hunter commenting on the good and bad sides of working with Lee St</span>
  <span id="freeText18148795549227183590" style="display:none">This book gets five stars for what's best about it, the insights it gives into women (and some men) who were important collaborators with Tennessee Williams. In particular, Mr. Grissom provides rare biographical insights on such neglected actresses as Lois Smith, Barbara Baxley, Jo van Fleet, Kim Hunter and Kim Stanley. As a running subtheme, there's also a history of the Actor's Studio, with Maureen Stapleton, Geraldine Page and Hunter commenting on the good and bad sides of working with Lee Strasberg. To get to all this wonderful material, you have to get through Grissom's account of his work with Williams, who, late in life, comes off as something of a bore.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18148795549227183590" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
